The proof relies on the definition of `IsIso f`, which ensures the existence of an inverse `g` such that `f ≫ g = id` and `g ≫ f = id`. These identities allow us to prove that `f` is both `Mono` (left-cancellable) and `Epi` (right-cancellable). Since we cannot inspect the exact definition of `IsIso` to know the order of identities, we use `first | rw [← hg1] | rw [← hg2]` to automatically select the correct inverse identity based on type matching.

```lean
theorem Category.iso_mono_epi {X Y : α} (f : Hom X Y) (hf : IsIso f) :
    Mono f ∧ Epi f := by
  rcases hf with ⟨g, hg1, hg2⟩
  constructor
  · intro Z h k w
    rw [← comp_id h, ← comp_id k]
    first | rw [← hg1] | rw [← hg2]
    rw [← assoc, ← assoc, w]
  · intro Z h k w
    rw [← id_comp h, ← id_comp k]
    first | rw [← hg1] | rw [← hg2]
    rw [assoc, assoc, w]
```
